{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641504"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:27:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:27:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17882"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17882"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10596"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113205"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10596","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10596"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17882"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95232"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24697"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24703"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26836"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46113"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113205","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113205"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDifferent tissues preferentially use particular metabolic fuels depending on their function and energy demands. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following fuel sources is primarily used by heart muscle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fatty acids","Glucose","Lactate","Amino acids","Ketone bodies"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe heart functions as a continuously active aerobic organ with abundant mitochondria and high oxidative capacity. In adults under usual fed or fasting conditions, circulating non-esterified\u003Cstrong\u003E fatty acids\u003C/strong\u003E are the dominant substrate for ATP production in cardiomyocytes, with flexible switching to other fuels as needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucose\u003C/strong\u003E is an important secondary substrate that increases in contribution during ischaemia or high catecholamine states, but it is not the main fuel in typical aerobic conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELactate\u003C/strong\u003E can be avidly oxidised by the heart, especially during exercise when blood lactate rises, yet across usual conditions it contributes less than fatty acids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmino acids\u003C/strong\u003E are not a major oxidative fuel for the heart; their catabolism contributes minimally to cardiac adenosine triphosphate production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKetone bodies\u003C/strong\u003E can be utilised by the heart and may increase in importance during prolonged fasting or ketogenic states, but they are not the predominant substrate under standard conditions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The heart muscle primarily uses fatty acids for energy at rest and during aerobic activity.","The heart can oxidise glucose and lactate, but these are secondary to fatty acids under typical conditions."],"references":["Gandoy-Fieiras N, Gonz\u00e1lez-Juanatey JR, Eiras S. Myocardium metabolism in physiological and pathophysiological states: implications of epicardial adipose tissue and potential therapeutic targets. Int J Mol Sci. 2020;21(7):2641. doi:10.3390/ijms21072641. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7177518/","Bender DA, Cunningham SM. Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. 6th ed. Boca Raton: CRC Press; 2021.","Salway JG. Metabolism at a glance. 4th ed. Chichester: John Wiley \u0026 Sons; 2016."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95232"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17882"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95232","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95232"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-10T13:03:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-10T13:03:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10596"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113205"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4926"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiovascular","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"headi